Service Interruption: Internet Access

We have located the issue with our recent Internet outages. The provider of our primary Internet connection is having a Denial of Service attack which is affecting our Internet. We have moved over to our secondary Internet connection while our Internet Service Provider (ISP) works on their issues. Due to the decreased speed of our secondary ISP users may notice slower speeds.

Remote learners will still have issues connecting because they will not be able to connect to Lightspeed which goes through our primary ISP.

We apologize for any inconvenience and appreciate your patience.

post_text:
Good morning EACS Families,



Last night the EACS Board of School Trustees gave their consensus to move forward with the Reopening Plan. The plan will return to the Board of School Trustees on August 4th with some additional details for their approval. Attached to this message you will find the ‚ÄúEACS Reopening Plan at a Glance‚Äù. If you would like to see the ‚ÄùFull Reopening Plan‚Äù, please go to the EACS website at www.eacs.k12.in.us. Also, just a reminder that online registration begins July 24th and ends July 31. Thank you for your support in the days and weeks ahead!



Thank you,

Marilyn S. Hissong

East Allen County Schools

Superintendent

post_text:
East Allen County Families,
The recent media releases you have seen on TV and heard on the radio are not our re-opening plan for the upcoming school year. The safety plan was a requirement from the Governor for schools to reopen during the summer for staff and essential student needs. It has been posted on our website since May 11th. The plan has not been updated since that date. I do want to reassure you that we will be working to create our re-entry plan in the days and weeks ahead and will communicate it with all of you. The plan will be evolving based on the current situation. In the meantime, stay safe and enjoy your summer!
text:
East Allen County Families,
The recent media releases you have seen on TV and heard on the radio are not our re-opening plan for the upcoming school year. The safety plan was a requirement from the Governor for schools to reopen during the summer for staff and essential student needs. It has been posted on our website since May 11th. The plan has not been updated since that date. I do want to reassure you that we will be working to create our re-entry plan in the days and weeks ahead and will communicate it with all of you. The plan will be evolving based on the current situation. In the meantime, stay safe and enjoy your summer!

Safety Village is a rite of passage field trip for our Kindergarten students and we were so sad when COVID-19 closed our schools and our Kinders didn't get to go. The Fort Wayne Police Department understood this and opened up summer days for schools to visit Safety Village! NHP's Safety Village Days were June 1, 2, and 3, where families could bring their kinder to Safety Village at certain times and students could still participate in this fun and important field trip! Thank you FWPD and Safety Village officers for making it so our students could still attend!
